cenames derive from Old English <i>horh</i> or <i>horu</i> ‘dirt, filth’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some may have different origins, including Horton in Gloucestershire, which may derive from Old English <i>heorot</i> ‘hart, stag’ + <i>tūn</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hortin","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  ."]},{"name":"Horten","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farms named Horten, from an unattested word denoting ‘uneven, hard and lumpy soil’."]}]},{"name":"Owen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Modern form of the Welsh name Owain  or a transferred use of the surname derived from the personal name. It is also used as an Anglicized form of Gaelic    <b>Eóghan</b>    (see Scottish and Irish appendices), which is probably ultimately a cognate of the Welsh name. Although retaining its Welsh flavour, this is one of a number of Celtic names which have recently come into general use and have become increasingly popular since the 1990s."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":11,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Owen De Horton was born in 1248, in Cheshire, England, his father, Henry de Horton, was 33 and his mother, Lady Elia de Horton, was 29. He married Tegengle DeHorton in 1267, in Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1272, in his hometown, at the age of 24."},"et":{"1248–1272":"1248–1272","1240–1332":"1240–1332","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1252–Female":"1252–Surnud","1250–1320":"1250–1320","1268–1328":"1268–1328"